<section>
  <title>Executive summary: trigonometric integrals</title>
  <introduction>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Theory</title>
    <theorem>
      <title>Trigonometric identities</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The following identities hold for all <m>\theta, \phi\in\mathbb{R}</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\cos\theta\cos\phi=\frac{\cos(\theta-\phi)+\cos(\theta+\phi)}{2}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\sin\theta\sin\phi=\frac{\cos(\theta-\phi)-\cos(\theta+\phi)}{2}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\sin\theta\cos\phi= \frac{\sin(\theta-\phi)+\sin(\theta+\phi)}{2}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\cos^2\theta=\frac{1+\cos2\theta}{2}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\sin^2\theta=\frac{1-\cos2\theta}{2}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Procedures</title>
    <theorem>
      <title>Integrating $\sin^m x\cos^n x$</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> be nonnegative integers.
          When computing
          <me>
            \int \sin^m x\cos^n x\, dx
          </me>
          the following strategies often help.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>m=2k+1</m> is odd, write
                <me>
                  \int \sin^m x\cos^n x\, dx=\int (1-\cos^2x)^k\cos^n x\sin x\, dx
                </me>
                and use the substitution <m>u=\sin x, du=\cos x\, dx</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>n=2k+1</m> is odd, write
                <me>
                  \int \sin^m x\cos^n x\, dx=\int \sin^m x(1-\sin^2x)^k\cos x \, dx
                </me>
                and use the substitution <m>u=\cos x, du=-\sin x\, dx</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are both even use <m>\displaystyle\sin^2 x=\frac{1-\cos 2x}{2}</m> and
                <m>\displaystyle\cos^2 x=\frac{1+\cos 2x}{2}</m> to reduce to a lower power of <m>\cos 2x</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <theorem>
      <title>Integrating $\tan^m x\sec^n x$</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> be nonnegative integers.
          When computing
          <me>
            \int \tan^m x\sec^n x \, dx
          </me>
          the following strategies often help.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>m=2k+1</m> is odd and <m>n\geq 1</m>, write
                <me>
                  \int \tan^m x\sec^n x \, dx=\int (\sec^2 x-1)^k\sec^{n-1} x\sec x\tan x \, dx
                </me>
                and use the substitution <m>u=\sec x, du=\sec x\tan x\, dx</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>n=2k</m> is even, write
                <me>
                  \int \tan^m x\sec^n x \, dx=\int (\tan^2 x+1)^{k-1}\tan^m x\sec^2 x\, dx
                </me>
                and use the substitution <m>u=\tan x, du=\sec^2 x\, dx</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>m</m> is even and <m>n</m> is odd,
                express everything in terms of <m>\sec x</m> and possibly use integration by parts.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Examples</title>
    <p>
      Compute the following indefinite integrals.
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int \sin^3x \cos^2 x\, dx</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int \sin^2 x\cos^4 x\, dx</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int \sec^4 x\, dx</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int \tan^5 x\sec^7 x\, dx</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int \sec^3 x\, dx</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \int \tan^5 x \, dx</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>